00:50:55.040 --> 00:50:57.670
and such difficult coloratura.

00:50:57.670 --> 00:51:03.780
So -- and that be --
even more importantly.

00:51:03.780 --> 00:51:11.690
He became very attracted and
drawn to symbolist literature,

00:51:11.690 --> 00:51:15.220
which is very understated and
it's all about implication.

00:51:15.220 --> 00:51:17.240
It's not heart on the sleeve.

00:51:17.240 --> 00:51:21.070
It's all more inner.

00:51:21.070 --> 00:51:27.320
And because of that aesthetic
shift in his thinking.

00:51:27.320 --> 00:51:29.940
He would never have
composed a piece like this.

00:51:29.940 --> 00:51:35.110
So even after April of 1902,
when "Pelléas" was premiered

00:51:35.110 --> 00:51:39.400
and became incredibly popular.

00:51:39.400 --> 00:51:43.390
I mean, it just catapulted
him to fame overnight.

00:51:43.390 --> 00:51:49.370
The publishers were asking for more
works and he couldn't possibly keep

00:51:49.370 --> 00:51:54.860 position:56%
up with the demand, so he often went
into his old, you know, portfolios

00:51:54.860 --> 00:51:58.770
and "what can I resurrect and
slightly tweak and publish?"

00:51:58.770 --> 00:52:01.320
But he still chose not to do these.

00:52:01.320 --> 00:52:04.480
And I think it was
for aesthetic reasons.

